Analysing for Arrivals

p <- ggplot(arrivals,aes(x = Flag, y = Draft))
p <- p + geom_point( colour = "skyblue1")
p <- p + labs(title = "Harbour Ship arrivals Flags of different Countries vs Draft 2022", x = "Country Flag" , y = "Draft" )
p

The dot plot shows that Liberia and Malta has the highest Draft, followed by Cy The goem_point does not really show a good representation of the data at the it a bit difficult to differentiate the datas.

p <- ggplot(arrivals,aes(x = Flag, y = Draft))
p <- p + geom_line( colour = "tomato")
p <- p + labs(title = "Harbour Ship arrivals Flags of different Countries vs Draft 2022", x = "Country Flag" , y = "Draft" )
p <- p + ylim(3,20)
p

The dot plot shows that Liberia and Malta has the highest Draft, followed by Cy The goem_line is not good representation of this data as it is difficult to different them

p <- ggplot(arrivals,aes(x = Flag, y = Draft))
p <- p + geom_bar(width = 1, stat="identity", colour = "coral3")
p <- p + labs(title = "Harbour Ship arrivals Flags of different Countries vs Draft 2022", x = "Country Flag" , y = "Draft" )
p

The Bar chat shows that Liberia and Malta has the highest Draft, followed by Cy and the Countries with the flag TN and NO has the lowest Draft. The Bar chat is the best representation of the data as it shows a good and more clear difference of the data distribution.

Therefore I observed that the distributions compare between the 2 dataset indicates that vessels shows the highest and lowest comprising of vessels of different countries while Arrivals shows the comprising between the arrivals.

Task 3

checking the correlation

cor <- cor(vessel$Beam,vessel$Length)
cor
## [1] 0.9321226

The correlation coefficient is greater than 0.05 p-value. It shows a strong and positive association between them.It is suitable.

Prediciting the Beam

lm.output<-lm(formula= Beam~Length,data=vessel)
summary(lm.output)

## Call:
## lm(formula = Beam ~ Length, data = vessel)
